Lecture 1b: Visualization

Visualizing High Dimensional Data is Difficult. Hopf Fibration link

Two Paradigms: 1. Static Visualization: Snapshot of a data set(non-interactive) 1. Dynamic Visualization: A sequence of snapshots of data that a user can interact with (interactive)

Static: An example is a fixed generated graph. Dynamic: An example is a dashboard with filters or slicers. Or an animation.

Static Packages

There are several packages for static visualizations, Such as ggplot2. The Package, igraph, creates graphs. ggdendro creates dendrograms(like tree of life) and tree diagrams, and ggmap which visualizes dataframes over maps.

Dynamic Packages

ploty, for dynamic data frame visualization using dashboards, and gganimate which creates animations.

ggplot2

elements involved in a ggplot2 plot - data, aesthtic mappings, geometric objects - statistical transformations - scales coordinate system - facet

these elements are integrated via the package grammar

  • a plot maps data to visual elements via specific grammar
  • ggplot2 builds a plot layer by layer

Selecting a proper coordinate system is important for visualizatoin - cartesian with (x,y) pairs - polar with position and angle (think boat or plane… traveling north turn left heading 320)

Elementary Visualization

Using the mpg dataset, we will illustrate several instances of elemetary visualization including - scatter plot - density plot, histogram - boxplot - barplot, pie chart

These 6 plots are all about summary statistics. Scatter plot: correlation, clustering Density plot: frequencies Histogram: frequency for specific events in specific ranges Boxplot: five point summary (median, first quartile, 3rd quartile, relative min & max) Barplot: similar to histogram Pie Chart: Proportion, or frequencies if normalized

Density Plot

used to: - visually check the model assumptions - visually compare a response’s behavior under different conditions

when it comes to diagnostics, We don’t even need q-q plot if we estimate density properly

  1. how many modes do you see? 3 each of the peaks
  2. which density function shows a degree of skewness (right or left) compact(green) and suv(blue)
  3. if you look at the density plots, say something about the average? or can you? density does not tell you the average.
  4. within each class what is the most likely hwy technically there isnt one because the likelihood of a specific value for continuous variables is 0% but we can say that for example an suv the most likely range is \(14 \pm 2\).

\(\mu = E(X) = \int_a^b x f(X) dx = x_0 f(x_0) (b-a)\) for some \(x_0 \in [a,b]\) by Mean Value Theorem

Bar Plot

For some classes there are not enough observations to construct a bar. This is an unbalanced design, there is not an equal number of observations for each class.

Pie Chart

## # A tibble: 3 × 4
##   class       n percentage labels
##   <fct>   <int>      <dbl> <chr> 
## 1 suv        62     0.544  54%   
## 2 compact    47     0.412  41%   
## 3 2seater     5     0.0439 4%

- group data via class, obtain counts for each class, compute percentages from counts, and arrange classes by their descending percentages - caution ungroup() is needed after group_by(…) %>% count() - The best selling chart is the pie chart?

  • coord_polar converts bar plot into pie chart
  • theme_void() mean “a completely empty theme; otherwise the resulting pie chart does not look nice
  • geom_text adds labels to label different parts of a plot at their designated positions
  • labels in mpg2 is used to label the slices.
